node.text:
If all of your debts are paid in full and the accounts are closed, you'll have what's called an "indeterminable" credit score after about 6 months. Then, you'll be able to do what's called "manual underwriting" to buy a home. All that means is that the mortgage company will do what banks used to do all the time when someone bought a home. They'll actually review your finances to check out whether or not you're in a position to pay back the loan.

A mortgage is the only type of debt, I'm okay with. Just make sure that the payment is no more than 25% of your take-home pay on no more than a 15-year mortgage at a fixed rate. I want your house to be a financial blessing in your life, not a financial curse.

You CAN have financial peace. You just need to take your time and do the math to make sure things are done right.

Thanks to Dr. @johndelony for joining me on this call. 

#debtfreecommunity 
#mortgage

node.text:
There's an addictive thrill that can come with the risk on these sorts of things. Although a lot of people are having a lot of fun with this right now, it's important to not confuse a get-rich-quick scenario with an actual, proven wealth-building plan. Just because a few people won the lottery one time does NOT make it an investment strategy that you should use. If you're debt-free with a full emergency fund, and you want to use some fun/entertainment money that you've budgeted for to play around with these things, I'm not gonna get mad at you, but I don't recommend it… and I certainly don't do this myself. If you REALLY want to play around with single stocks, just make sure that no more than 10% of your net worth is tied up in them. This is to ensure that things don't go overboard to the point that it can actually impact your net worth in a negative way if and when things go south. 

Reminder: I only recommend investing in mutual funds and real estate that's paid for in full. 

#debtfreecommunity

node.text:
Great conversation with @kencoleman.

Budgeting isn't easy at first, but it's worth it. You've got to push through a few months to learn how to get your budget right. It's only when the pain of where you are exceeds the pain of making the change that you will actually decide to CHANGE. The struggle at the beginning is part of the learning process.

Push through— you'll get there. You can do this! 💪

#debtfreecommunity

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 10, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'The Difference between Saving and Investing A savings account is for money that you'll use within the next five years If you're willing to leave that money alone for more than five years, then you can invest it.'.

node.text:
Remember that this also depends on which Baby Step you're on. Choosing between saving money and investing money comes AFTER you've completed the first few Baby Steps.

If you're just getting started with Baby Step 1, you don't need to invest yet, even if you wish you could. The priority at the beginning of your Baby Step journey should be to get your $1,000 starter emergency fund saved so you can knock out debt in Baby Step 2.

If you have FINISHED paying off debt and have your full 3-6 months of expenses saved for Baby Step 3, you can then move on to Baby Step 4. This is where you invest 15% of your income toward retirement. Baby Steps 4, 5, and 6 are done at the same time, but in order. Once you've put 15% of your income toward retirement investing, you can decide how much you want to also put toward Baby Step 5, which is saving for your kids college. Then, you put extra money toward paying off your home early for Baby Step 6. During this more stable time in your financial journey, you're able to make decisions about saving vs. investing. You've freed yourself up to do some extra saving in sinking funds for things you'll need within the next few years, and once your home is paid off, you can make some fun investing decisions for your long-term goals.

Remember to take things one step at a time, it really works, and you CAN do it.

#debtfreecommunity

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 10, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of 1 person and text that says 'Dave Ramsey @DaveRamsey Having a mortgage is like having a backache. You get used to it and orget it's there, but when it's gone, you will notice.'.

node.text:
The grass under your feet feels different when it's all YOURS.

If you're ready to buy a home, make sure it's one you can really afford. Get a mortgage that's no more than 25% of your monthly take-home pay at a 15-year, fixed-rate. If a real estate agent tries to pressure you to buy a home that's more than that, they're not a great agent. You deserve someone who will walk alongside you and respect your budget. 

My team vets top agents all around the country who have the heart of a teacher to help you find the right home for you and your budget.

🏡 Click the link in my profile to get in touch with one in your area! 

#debtfreecommunity
#realestate

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 10, 2021. May be an image of text that says 'THERE'S NO SUCH THING AS "EASY PAYMENTS."'.

node.text:
Debt will ALWAYS hold you back from your goals. Get it out of your life as fast as you can. 

Change your habits from asking "how much per month?", to just, "how much?".

If you can't pay cash for something, you can't afford it... and that's okay. Walk away. You'll get there soon enough. You just have to hustle and grind to get those "easy payments" out of your life first.

You got this! 💪

(The only debt I won't get mad about is a mortgage, but make sure it's a 15-year, fixed-rate, where the payment is no more than 25% of your monthly take-home pay.) 

#debtfreecommunity

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 09, 2021. May be an image of 3 people, people standing, outdoors and text that says 'WE ARE DEBT FREE ANNA We Paid Off $45,850i $45,850in2 21 Months!'.

node.text:
WOW!! So awesome. Well done, and THANK YOU for your service! 

#repost @brookevillalpando

Screaming from all the rooftops and from across the world (literally) 😆 We officially are DEBT FREE!

A little over a year and a half ago Ty sent me an excel spreadsheet of all our debt and claimed we could pay it all off in 33 months. I did not believe him but I was onboard with paying off our debt as soon as possible so that we no longer owed anybody anything. Here we are accomplishing our goal 12 months early!

Between student loans, vehicle loans, and a few other small loans we chipped away each month using @daveramsey as our guidance.

Thank you @daveramsey for being an inspiration and for being our motivation during these last 21 months. We are officially free!!

#debtfreecommunity
#debtfreescream

#debtfreecommunity

#debtfreecommunity

node.accessibility_caption: Photo by Dave Ramsey on September 08, 2021. May be a Twitter screenshot of 1 person and text that says 'Dave Ramsey @DaveRamsey 79% of millionaires didn't receive any inheritance at all from their parents or other family members. Millionaires aren't born. They're built. You can get there too.'.

node.text:
On top of that, only 3% of millionaires actually inherited 1 million dollars or more.

It's time to quit believing the lies we've been told. My team conducted the largest study of millionaires EVER, and the truth is, a huge majority of millionaires are self-made. They weren't just lucky, or born into the "right" families. They lived on less than they made, avoided debt, saved, and invested their money wisely.

It's not too late for you. Start making wise money decisions now, like saving an emergency fund, and getting out of debt as quickly as you can, so you can begin investing sooner rather than later.

You got this!

#debtfreecommunity
#millionaire

Wise words from Christy Wright. Your life is up to YOU and the decisions you make about your time.

Christy's latest book will teach you how to literally "Take Back Your Time". It's the guilt-free guide to life balance, and it releases in just ONE WEEK. If you preorder, you'll get the E-book, the Audiobook, and access to join Christy's Take Back Your Time Livestream Event next Thursday evening.

🔗Go to ramseysolutions.com to reserve your copy! 

#repost @christybwright

We live by our calendars and to-do lists. And we’ll never feel balanced if we spend our time and energy showing up to commitments we don’t care about and checking off boxes on lists that don’t really even matter. That’s why we have to put our priorities on paper on purpose. When we begin to align our calendars and to-do lists with what actually matters, we will not only get the right things done, but we’ll actually have more fun and feel more balanced as well. — Excerpt from my upcoming book Take Back Your Time, The Guilt-Free Guide to Life Balance 

#takebackyourtime #lifebalance #debtfreecommunity

Well done!! Less than a year into your marriage, and you don't owe a payment to anyone. SO cool. 

#repost @elainahuizenga

Debt free in 1 year!!! 🎉🎉🎉

Thanks to @daveramsey we have completed baby step 2. Student loans and a car loan for a total of $43,899.76.

It seemed like it was going to take a long time when we started a year ago right before we got married. Now we have been married for 10 month and started new jobs. We worked longer hours, did side jobs and sold a car to pay off our debt quicker.

#debtfreecommunity
#debtfreescream
